@NODE "Usage" "Part 55 - The INFO Command - Usage"


@{B}@{U}The INFO Command Usage@{UB}@{UU}

In its simplest form this command is used without any arguments or
keywords:-

  INFO

Or it can be used with the @{"DEVICE" LINK "Device"} option.

The information it displays is illustrated by this example output:-

  Mounted disks:
  Unit      Size    Used    Free Full Errs   Status   Name
  RAM:      145K     145       0 100%   0  Read/Write Ram Disk
  DH0:     4095K    7781     409  95%   0  Read Only  Workbench2.1
  DF0:      No disk present
  DF1:      837K    1648     110  94%   0  Read/Write Games
  DH1:       10M   21387    1139  95%   0  Read Only  Work

  Volumes available:
  Games
  Ram Disk [Mounted]
  Work [Mounted]
  Workbench2.1 [Mounted]

The first section shows all available drives and details of the disk (if
any) in them under the headings:-

@{B}Unit@{UB}   - the device name
@{B}Size@{UB}   - total disk capacity in kilobytes (K) or megabytes (M)
@{B}Used@{UB}   - number of disk blocks currently in use
@{B}Free@{UB}   - number of disk blocks still free for use
@{B}Full@{UB}   - percentage of disk capacity in use
@{B}Errs@{UB}   - number of disk errors found on validation
@{B}Status@{UB} - Whether the disk is readable and writable or readable only.
@{B}Name@{UB}   - The name of the volume (disk) in the drive

Note that a hard drive has each of its partitions mentioned as separate
devices.

The second section gives the names of the volumes (disks or hard drive
partitions) available. They will mostly have "[Mounted]" after them
indicating that they are physically in the drive. However, if the
"[Mounted]" is missing (as in the "Games" disk in the table) it means that
the system still has some reference to the disk even though it is not
physically in a drive. This can happen if one of the disk's windows is
still open, or if an assignment has been made to that disk or one of its
directories.


